Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you donâ€™t have symptoms.

Seychelles has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Seychelles, see Return to the UK.
Entry and borders
Entry to Seychelles is not currently possible on commercial flights. The international Airport will remain closed until June 2020.
No marine vessel or aircraft is permitted to enter, exit, transit or leave Seychelles, without the permission of the Ministry of Health, until further notice.
Cruise ships from any country worldwide will not be permitted to berth in Seychelles until further notice and passengers from cruise ships will not be permitted to disembark. If you have made plans to travel to or from Seychelles by cruise ship, then you should contact your tour operator for further information.
Local measures
The Seychellios authorities introduced a lockdown from 9 April.
As of 4 May 2020, restrictions on movement in Seychelles have eased, but some restrictions remain in place until further notice.
Restaurants and shops may open again, but must close at 8pm. Bars and clubs are to remain closed until further notice. People may return to work, but the prohibition of public assemblies and public events will continue. People are also prohibited from gathering in groups of more than four until further notice. Parties and beach gatherings are not allowed. House parties, which include any person from outside the immediate household, are prohibited.
Restrictions are enforceable by law and can change at short notice. You should consult the Department of Health in Seychelles for further information and monitor local media for the latest developments.
Further information
Further advice on coronavirus is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
For information on how to return to the UK from Seychelles, see Return to the UK.
